   By Saabira Chaudhuri 
 Forest City Enterprises Inc. (FCEA, FCEB) said Bruce Ratner will step down as chief executive of Brooklyn-based unit Forest City Ratner Co., effective immediately, and it named MaryAnne Gilmartin, its executive vice president of commercial and residential development, to succeed him. Mr. Ratner will serve as executive chairman of Forest City Ratner Co., or FCRC. Forest billed the transition as being part of the company's ongoing succession planning, reiterating a view it offered in January, when it responded to media reports that Mr. Ratner intended to step down. At the time, Forest said it had no definitive announcement to make on potential leadership succession. FCRC, which has built such recognizable projects as the new Barclays Center basketball arena in Brooklyn and the New York Times building in Midtown Manhattan, was helmed by founder Bruce Ratner, who sold his stake to Forest City Enterprises seven years ago. Mr. Ratner is a prolific developer who has spent the past three decades successfully battling for public approvals of large and often controversial projects. His company pioneered downtown Brooklyn development in the 1980s with its MetroTech project that became a big success. But Forest City also launched many big projects in the years leading up to the economic downturn and some of them have fallen short of projections. Meanwhile, Ms. Gilmartin joined FCRC in 1994. During her 18-year tenure, she has been involved in a number of the company's most visible projects in the region, including Barclays Center arena, New York by Gehry at 8 Spruce Street and the New York Times Building. She began her career in real estate in 1986 as a New York City urban fellow at the Public Development Corporation. "Under the leadership of Bruce Ratner, the New York metropolitan area has become our largest core market and a key component of our overall value-creation model," Forest City Enterprises CEO David J. LaRue said. "We are thrilled that MaryAnne Gilmartin will continue this legacy and assume day-to-day leadership of FCRC as president and CEO, and that Bruce will continue to play a key role as executive chairman. " Write to Saabira Chaudhuri at saabira.chaudhuri@dowjones.com Email
