Zach,I do not claim to have the full knowledge and understanding of the omnipotent God, but I have studied and prayed and sought to understand what He has revealed, and as a result have made certain logical conclusions as to why God allows and does what he does, and what this world is all about and where it is all going. The first step for me was to understand the words and concepts used in the Bible. I remember reading Revelation and thinking it was odd there was a lamb in heaven. Then I learned that Christ was portrayed as a lamb who takes away the sins of the world. So I had to learn the Old Testament and the role of the lamb. I had to learn the difference between the Old and New Testaments and the reasons for them, and then I came across the teaching that God had planned it all before the very creation of the world. I can't tell you the number of times in discussions like this one when someone would show me a contradiction in the Bible and tell me I was a fool to believe it. I read the contradiction and realized they were right. Then I looked closer, I prayed, I studied and found they were not right. They lacked understanding. That bolstered my faith in the teaching, and the next time I was not so quick to accept the critics accusations. After years of this, my understanding has increased. Do I know it all? No. Do I know more than I did to begin with? Yes, a lot more. I view the Scripture as a large picture that reveals a truth, and the more I put into place, the clearer the picture becomes. I don't think someone who rejects the Bible outright can do that.As I said a few posts ago, Greg views as unreasonable the sacrifice of Jesus for our sins. He only sees a "God who sacrificed himself to himself to save mankind from himself?" Ugh. I can't tell you the number of times I've heard that very same criticism. I know the answer, but how do I communicate it to someone who has no knowledge of the very basics of my faith? Our discussion began with questioning the understanding of why God allows what he allows. Imagine how frustrating it is for me to have to defend the fact that God understands English. That his logic concerning the world and what he allows to happen has no bearing on the fact that he can understand and communicate with man. In fact, he has done it in two ways, through his written word, the Bible, and the living Word, Christ. If you want to know the innermost thoughts of God expressed outwardly to you--the Logos--it is Christ.
