Nancy:“We learn a language through association and repetition.”Association and repetition are cognitive tasks. Cognitive tasks are accomplished via cognitive processes. Tasks like association and repetition are accomplished via a process called inference. Inference is a logical process in which the brain identifies X as X because it infers that X is X based on previous associations. “I cannot use logic to determine what they call that curved yellow fruit in English. Someone has to teach me that it is called a banana.”Oh, now I think I see where the problem is. Let’s try something else:1.	P - The teacher shows you a curved yellow fruit and tells you it is called a banana.2.	P - You believe that the teacher is telling you the truth.3.	Q – Thus, you now know that the curved yellow fruit is called a banana.The same syllogism in symbol form:1.	P – X says Y is Z.2.	P – X is true.3.	Q – Thus, Y is Z.That’s the logical thought process used to make initial linguistic associations. In psychology, this is called inference. These associations are also reinforced logically. For example:1.	P – Your mother calls a curved yellow fruit a banana, just like your teacher.2.	P – If your mom calls a curved yellow fruit a banana, you have no reason to believe your teacher was lying.3.	Q – Thus, you know that a curved yellow fruit is still called a banana.Without inference, which is the “process of deriving logical conclusions from premises known or assumed to be true”, none of these associations can happen. Isn’t that obvious by now? Your teacher tells you the yellow fruit is called a banana—that’s the first premise. You assume that your teacher is telling the truth—that’s the second premise. The yellow fruit is called a banana—that’s the logical conclusion you derive from those premises.“I have searched and searched the internet to find something that tells me you need logic to understand a language.”That’s part of the problem; you have no formal training in this, so you don’t even know 