Nancy:“With this explanation I still don't see how logic precedes language, but would say that man's ability to use language is an important part of human cognition. From that we can use language to reason and use logic.”I urge you to re-read the paragraph I quoted very closely. Pinker says that “[o]bject terms are natural primary argument terms.” What he means by this is that every word for an object is a specific argument to define that object. An argument is “an attempt to persuade someone of something, by giving reasons or evidence for accepting a particular conclusion.” For example, every time you use the word “banana” in conversation or writing, you are issuing a small argument to your audience that banana refers to that curved yellow fruit. Your argument is based on inductive reasoning (a type of logical thought); you are implicitly saying, “I posit that the word ‘banana’ refers to a curved yellow fruit.” Now, the English language (for example) is a relatively efficient form of communication precisely because—for an argument as simple as an object term—you rarely have to support this argument with inductive premises. In other words, most people will instantly accept your argument and move onto the rest of what you are trying to communicate. That doesn’t mean, however, that the argument isn’t still there. You can see these arguments manifest themselves when people debate the meaning of certain words, in which they must rely on the aforementioned inductive premises to construct a logical argument.As a side note, recent neurological studies suggest that humans do not rely upon language to engage in logical thought.
