By
Ted Mann
Updated Oct. 27, 2012 2:46 p.m. ET
New York state officials said that they will decide on Sunday whether to proceed with a shutdown of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority in advance of the approaching Hurricane Sandy. Warning of potential high winds and flooding that could trigger a decision to shutter all or part of the system, MTA Chairman Joseph Lhota
said such a move would start at 7 p.m. on Sunday if necessary. On its current course, Sandy appears likely to make landfall south of New York City, which could generate storm surges of 4 to 8 feet and major flooding in low-lying areas of the city and the subway system. The MTA and the state aren't yet ordering a shutdown, but are making preparations for that possibility, and seeking to prompt rail and bus riders to make plans for cuts in service leading into the work week. "Try to be home or be where you need to be at 7 p.m., because there is no guarantee of service after that," Mr. Lhota said in a televised briefing from Gov. Andrew Cuomo's office in Midtown. "We're planning for the worst, we're hoping for the best, and all decisions will be made on this tomorrow," Mr. Lhota said. Patrick Foye, the executive director of the Port Authority of New York & New Jersey, said flight operations were continuing as normal at LaGuardia, Kennedy and Newark Liberty international airports. But passengers should check with airlines before traveling to the airport as the storm approaches. Major effects of Sandy are expected to begin reaching the New York region Monday morning. State Health Commissioner Nirav Shah said the state has begun a limited evacuation of ventilator-dependent patients in "a few facilities" located in the storm's "slosh zone"—a term connoting "sea, lake and overland surges from hurricanes." The MTA is seeking to avoid a repeat of its shutdown during Hurricane Irene, Mr. Lhota said, adding, "We don't want that to happen." But the agency has no choice but to prepare. In addition to a shutdown of the transit system, which would be called for in the event of a storm with sustained winds of 39 miles per hour or higher, the MTA will call for a slowdown order on its bridges in the event of high winds. Every MTA bridge will be shut down in the event that winds reach 60 miles per hour, Mr. Lhota said.
