LAFAYETTE, La. -- Democratic Sen. Mary Landrieu says she generally backs President Barack Obama's health-care overhaul efforts. But she'd like to see a few items in the bill before voting for it, including bigger federal Medicaid payments for her home state of Louisiana, extended health coverage for her pet cause of foster children, and help for teaching hospitals in her state. While pushing more spending in those areas, Ms. Landrieu also wants the plan to cut the overall amount the nation spends on health care. On the Table Compare the plans, point-by-point
Health-Care Overhaul Attempts As costs have risen, attempts at change
View Graphics
Washington Wire: What to Watch in House Vote House Democrats Push for Saturday Vote More interactive graphics and photos Video: Another Missed Health Deadline Democrats See Health Timetable Slipping Journal Community Vote: Should the House pass the bill? As Democratic leaders enter the intensive phase of their drive to pass health legislation, they must satisfy 60 Mary Landrieus in the Senate -- every Democrat and the two Democratic-friendly independents, each with individual priorities -- as they try to hold together a fragile coalition with no room for error. And that has only become more complicated as Democrats from conservative states puzzle over what to make of Republican victories Tuesday in governor's races in Virginia and New Jersey. Senators' needs vary greatly, and sometimes contradict each other. Sen. Evan Bayh (D., Ind.) is a big supporter of medical-device makers in Indiana, and he signed a letter declaring himself "extremely concerned" about a proposed tax on the industry. Sen. Blanche Lincoln (D., Ark.), facing a tough re-election contest next year, would like to tackle the shortage of health providers in rural areas. Sen. Bob Menendez (D., N.J.) is pushing a tax break for investments in start-up biotechnology firms, earning him plaudits from his state's burgeoning biotech industry. Dozens of other senators have their own priorities. Beyond that, Democrats from conservative states are under particular pressure to show their voters the health bill is not too expensive, won't create a vast bureaucracy, and will help business. Majority Leader Harry Reid's decision to include a government-run competitor to private insurers -- commonly dubbed "the public option" -- greatly intensifies the pressure to satisfy all 58 Democrats and two independents in the Senate, since it is now unlikely any Republicans will support the bill. Sixty votes are needed to block a filibuster and bring the bill to the Senate floor, though if that obstacle is overcome and the bill comes up for a vote, passage will require only a simple majority of 51. Enlarge Image
Louisiana Sen. Mary Landrieu at a health-insurance news conference Tuesday.
Getty Images It may take special concessions to keep on board a handful of Democrats uneasy with the "public option," like Ms. Landrieu. The senator, a member of a venerable Louisiana political family who has a quiet, matter-of-fact style, faces constant peril as a Democrat in a conservative state. Republican presidential candidate John McCain won Louisiana with 59% of the vote. Louisiana Democrats lost loyal voters when Hurricane Katrina drove away thousands of residents in 2005, many of them African-American and poor. Ms. Landrieu, 53 years old, won her first Senate election in 1996 in a runoff, prevailing by about 6,000 votes out of 1.7 million cast. In 2008, she was widely considered the most vulnerable Senate Democrat, and in a heavily Democratic year she garnered 52% of the vote. Along the way, she has become expert at walking a delicate line, a trait on full display as she navigates what could be the most important vote of her career. Ms. Landrieu sprinkles her sentences with "generally," giving her wiggle room, as in, "Generally, I'm just not in favor of a public option." In a tribute to her balancing act, she is one of the few politicians in America to be endorsed by both the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and the AFL-CIO. Detractors see in that deftness a willingness to change her message depending on the audience. "She's laid out a clear stand saying she doesn't want a public option, but she's also said she's willing to compromise," said Aaron Baer, spokesman for the Louisiana Republican Party. "Here in the state, she's strongly against the public option; when she's back in D.C., it's all about how she's still working on a compromise." A spokesman for Ms. Landrieu declined to comment on that criticism. A recent forum at the Clifton Chenier community center in Lafayette illustrated her challenge. About 100 conservative protesters gathered outside, carrying signs reading, "No Mary No" and "Wake up Mary -- vote no!" A "Don't Tread on Me" flag flew from a nearby trailer. When Ms. Landrieu showed up, she surprised the protesters by wading into their midst. One called out, "If cloture is needed, would you vote for or against it?" referring to a move to block a filibuster. She replied, "It depends what's in the bill," prompting a collective "Ohhh" of disgust. The protesters appeared split over whether to shout the senator down or hear her out. When one yelled, "This is about [government] control!" another responded, "Let her talk!" As Ms. Landrieu walked away, the crowd broke into a chant of "Kill the bill!" John Estabrooks, a beret-clad local leader of the "tea party" movement, a group of anti-big-government activists, climbed onto a makeshift stage and told the crowd: "If Mary fails us, we will vote her out." Medicare is now on the verge of collapse. Same thing will happen to everyone's insurance if this bill passes. — Michael Landskroner
Inside, there was more support for the health overhaul. But Adam Mouton, 67, a retired Army officer clutching an American flag, asked Ms. Landrieu why Congress was changing the entire health system when only parts were broken. "You do agree that we have the best health-care system in the world?" he demanded. Ms. Landrieu responded cautiously that the U.S. spends the most on health care but several countries boast better outcomes, prompting Mr. Mouton to shout, "Name one!" Ms. Landrieu said at first she was not sure, then named Sweden, and added hastily, "But I'm not for the Swedish system. I'm for our system." The U.S. Chamber of Commerce ran four ads in Louisiana and is mounting a campaign that claims to have attracted 13,000 signatures against "government-run" health care. A "Hands Off My Health Care" bus tour sponsored by the conservative Americans for Prosperity hit eight Louisiana cities in August. AFL-CIO officials lobbied Ms. Landrieu recently in her office to back the public option. Democratic leaders are keenly aware of these pressures and of their need to keep Ms. Landrieu in the fold. Senate Majority Leader Reid's first challenge is to win a vote to begin Senate consideration of the health bill. If that succeeds, it will set off a weeks-long debate, featuring numerous amendments and a good deal of horse-trading, culminating in a vote on passage of the bill. Enlarge Image
Sen. Maria Cantwell (D., Wash.), left, and Sen. Landrieu (D. La.) at a Senate hearing in June; both face votes soon on a health-care overhaul.
Associated Press Ms. Landrieu has faced such pressure for months. A group called Conservatives for Patients' Rights, which opposes a public option, aired ads in Louisiana featuring a bow-tied government bureaucrat standing between a patient and her kindly doctor. Ads from liberal MoveOn.org, which favors a public option, show a breast-cancer survivor from New Orleans asking Ms. Landrieu, "Whose side are you on?" Mr. Reid has cautioned that there is a long way to go and wary senators may come around. Senate Minority Leader Mitch McConnell (R., Ky.) predicts Mr. Reid will have difficulty persuading moderate Democrats. "I think the majority leader's probably having a challenging time trying to convince his members to go to a bill that cuts Medicare half a trillion dollars, raises taxes $400 billion, and raises insurance premiums," Mr. McConnell said. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi (D., Calif.) faces a daunting task of her own in holding together a majority for the overhaul. If both chambers approve their health bills, a conference committee will merge them, and then the Senate and House must vote separately on final passage. If that happens, Republican leaders may face their own challenge keeping their troops in line. Some Democrats predict that at least a handful of GOP members won't want to be seen as standing in the way of a historic expansion of health coverage. But the Democrats' quest is a treacherous one that could collapse at any moment, and Ms. Landrieu's importance to it is not lost on Democratic leaders. Mr. Reid met privately with her on Oct. 23, and she told him she had serious concerns about the public option but hoped for a quick compromise so the debate could move to other issues. Mr. Obama invited Ms. Landrieu to the Oval Office to sound her out, and he held a separate session with all of the Senate centrists. Ms. Landrieu has been gathering with these moderates a half-dozen times a week, in senators' offices and even hallways, to discuss impressions and ideas for health care. "It's sort of a gaggle, you know?" Ms. Landrieu said. "But we stay in touch with each other." The public option has been among the most contentious issues in the health-care debate, with critics complaining that a government-run insurer would compete unfairly with private insurers. In an attempted compromise between liberals and moderates, Mr. Reid's version of the public option would allow states to opt out if they chose. Ms. Landrieu's position on the public option depends on its final form; she suggests she would support a "fallback" under which it would kick in only if private insurers couldn't meet patients' needs. "I don't favor a government-run national public option," Ms. Landrieu said in a recent interview. "I could be open to either a fallback or a public option that plays on the same playing field as private business....Something like that I could maybe consider if it meant a deal at the end." Other concerns are tied more directly to her home state. About 20% of Louisiana's adults lack health insurance and 25% of its population is on Medicaid. Louisiana officials complain that federal and insurance money that poured into the state after Katrina artificially pumped up its reported income levels, requiring the state to pay a higher share of Medicaid costs. It's "a big, big problem for us in the state," said John Matessino, president of the Louisiana Hospital Association. "If it's not fixed, we could have a billion-dollar hole in the Medicaid program, and I don't even know how you run a Medicaid program at that point." Altering that formula is one of Ms. Landrieu's goals, one she raised directly with Mr. Reid when they met. Some of her aims are more personal. Her husband, Frank Snellings, and their two children, Connor and Mary Shannon, are all adoptees, and she has made adoption and foster care a top cause. She wants to provide health coverage through age 24 for anyone who has been in foster care at least six months. "This is sort of a special issue for me," Ms. Landrieu said. Her staff said it can't calculate the provision's cost or number of people affected because some move in and out of the foster-care system and many are covered by other programs such as Medicaid. Ms. Landrieu also heads the Senate's small-business committee, and her support of small business is a key way she has burnished her centrist credentials. In the health-care bill, Ms. Landrieu is pushing for small businesses to have access to a comprehensive health-insurance exchange, like the one some individuals would use. Louisiana political analysts say Ms. Landrieu can survive politically, even if many of her constituents dislike the health bill, so long as they believe she helped make it more conservative. "Anything that is even halfway as far as Obama wants to go will be too far for the average Louisiana voter," said Brian Brox, a political scientist at Tulane University. "I don't think there is a 'yes' vote that is not damaging for her. But if it doesn't have big government intervention or taxpayer funding of abortion, that is not as damaging." Write to Naftali Bendavid at naftali.bendavid@wsj.com Email
